ANALYTICS

Change

Case: Houston Minimum Temperature throughout the Years

Load the data

For this case, we extract the data from a pdf file, so extra steps maybe required.

df <- extract_tables("../archetypes/houston temp.pdf",
             output = "data.frame", guess = FALSE
             )

df <- reduce(df, bind_rows)
df <- df[-c(1,56:62,118:124, 129:134),]

df1 <- df[1:54,1:6]
df2 <- df[55:113,1:13]

foo <- data.frame(do.call('rbind', strsplit(as.character(df1$X.2),' ',fixed=TRUE)))
df1 <- cbind(df1, foo)
df1 <- df1 %>% select(-c(X.2,X.3,X.4),X.3, X.4)
names(df1) <- df1[1,]
df1 <- df1[-1,]
names(df2) <- names(df1)


df <- rbind(df1,df2)
head(df)
##   Year Jan Feb Mar Apr May Jun Jul Aug Sep Oct Nov Dec
## 3 1910  24  21  46  41  59  62  66  72  63  39  40  33

## 8 1915  28  40  32  40  57  66  67  64  62  52  35  30

Wrangle the data

Our dataframe is in a wide form. We will need to pivot it to a long form.

temp <- df

temp <- temp %>% pivot_longer(!Year, names_to = 'Month', values_to='Temperature')
temp <- temp[1:1338,]

temp$Month <- match(temp$Month, month.abb)
temp <- within(temp, Date <- sprintf("%s-%02d-01", Year, Month))


temp <- temp %>% select(Date, Temperature)
temp$Date <- as.Date(temp$Date)
temp$Temperature <- as.numeric(temp$Temperature)
head(temp)
## # A tibble: 6 x 2
##   Date       Temperature

Year 2000 - 2021

We will subset the data and plot it to have a clearer picture first.

temp00 <- temp[1081:1338,]

p <- ggplot(temp00, aes(x=Date, y=Temperature)) +
  geom_line() + 
  xlab("")
p

Well then perform a Bayesian analysis of change-points.

library(bcp)
bcp.1a <- bcp(temp00$Temperature)
plot(bcp.1a, return.mcmc = TRUE)

We now move on to Anomaly Detection. This Anomaly package was created by twitter to find anomalies in timeseries.

library(AnomalyDetection)

ano <- AnomalyDetectionVec(temp00$Temperature, period = 12, max_anoms=0.1,  direction = 'both', plot = T, alpha = 0.3)
ano$anoms
##   index anoms
## 1     9    49
## 2    27    22
## 3    51    47

## 7   237    71

paste0('Anomaly 1 :' ,temp00$Date[27])
## [1] "Anomaly 1 :2002-03-01"
paste0('Anomaly 2 :' ,temp00$Date[161])
## [1] "Anomaly 2 :2013-05-01"
paste0('Anomaly 3 :' ,temp00$Date[254])
## [1] "Anomaly 3 :2021-02-01"
ano$plot

We will use another Anomaly Detection Package. Unlike our Twitter package, this only recognizes Feb 2021 as an anomaly. This is when the winter storm happened in Houston, TX.

temp0 <- as_tibble(temp00)

library(anomalize)

df_anomalized <- temp0 %>%
    time_decompose(Temperature, merge = TRUE) %>%
    anomalize(remainder) %>%
    time_recompose()
df_anomalized %>% glimpse()

The package has a decomposition feature for further analysis.

p1 <- df_anomalized %>%
    plot_anomaly_decomposition() +
    ggtitle("Freq/Trend = 'auto'")
p1

p <- ggplot(temp, aes(x=Date, y=Temperature)) +

We now move on to Anomaly Detection

library(AnomalyDetection)

ano <- AnomalyDetectionVec(temp$Temperature, period = 12, max_anoms=0.4,  direction = 'both', plot = T)
x <- ano$anoms[,1]

for(i in x){
  print(paste0('Anomaly Dates :' , temp$Date[i]))
}
## [1] "Anomaly Dates :1930-01-01"
## [1] "Anomaly Dates :1989-12-01"
